  <page xml:id="p-2-3-imt-statement">
    <title>The Invertible Matrix Theorem</title>

    <p>
      Invertible matrices enjoy a rich set of equivalent descriptions.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-invertible-matrix-theorem">
      <title>The Invertible Matrix Theorem (IMT)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n\times n</m> matrix. The following statements are equivalent.
        </p>

        <ol marker="a)">
          <li><m>A</m> is invertible.</li>
          <li><m>A</m> is row equivalent to <m>I_n</m>.</li>
          <li><m>A</m> has <m>n</m> pivotal columns.</li>
          <li><m>A\vec x=\vec 0</m> has <em>only</em> the trivial solution.</li>
          <li>The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.</li>
          <li>The linear transformation <m>\vec x \mapsto A\vec x</m> is one-to-one.</li>
          <li>
            The equation <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a solution for all
            <m>\vec b\in\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
          </li>
          <li>The columns of <m>A</m> span <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</li>
          <li>The linear transformation <m>\vec x \mapsto A\vec x</m> is onto.</li>
          <li>
            There is an <m>n\times n</m> matrix <m>C</m> such that <m>CA=I_n</m>. (<m>A</m> has a left inverse.)
          </li>
          <li>
            There is an <m>n\times n</m> matrix <m>D</m> such that <m>AD=I_n</m>. (<m>A</m> has a right inverse.)
          </li>
          <li><m>A^T</m> is invertible.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-3-invertibility-composition">
    <title>Invertibility and Composition</title>

    <p>
      The diagram below provides another perspective on the role of the inverse matrix.
    </p>

    <image xml:id="img-invertibility-composition" width="80%">
      <latex-image >
        <latex>
\tikzstyle{startstop} =[trapezium, trapezium left angle=70, trapezium right angle=110,minimum width=1cm, minimum height=1cm, text centered, fill=DarkBlue!30]
\tikzstyle{arrow} = [thick,&lt;-,&gt;=stealth]

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]
  \node (x) [startstop] {$\vec x$};
  \node (ax) [startstop, right of=x, xshift=2cm, yshift=-2cm] {$A\vec x$};

  \draw [arrow] (ax) |- node[anchor=west] {\small Multiplication by $A$} (x);
  \draw [arrow] (x) |- node[anchor=east] {\small Multiplication by $A^{-1}$} (ax);
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex>
      </latex-image>
      <shortdescription>Diagram showing a transformation undone by its inverse.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        Diagram shows <m>\vec x</m>, transformed by multiplication by <m>A</m>, and reversed by multiplication by <m>A^{-1}</m>.
      </description>
    </image>

    <p workspace="0.5in">
      The matrix inverse <m>A^{-1}</m> transforms <m>A\vec x</m> back to <m>\vec x</m>, because <me>
      A^{-1}(A\vec x)=(A^{-1}A)\vec x=\vec x.
    </me>
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    


    <p> Some comments on IMT:
    <ul>
    <li>
        The Invertible Matrix Theorem divides all square matrices into two classes: invertible and non-invertible.
      </li>
      <li>
        As the course progresses, additional equivalent conditions involving determinants, eigenvalues, and other concepts will be added.
      </li>
        <li>Note that items (j) and (k) of the Invertible Matrix Theorem lead directly to the following result.</li>
      </ul>

    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-left-right-inverses" workspace="0.5in">
      <title>Left and Right Inverses</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n\times n</m> matrices and <m>AB=I</m>,
          then both matrices are invertible, with
          <m>B=A^{-1}</m> and <m>A=B^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>


 </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-3-example-completion">

    <example xml:id="ex-check-invertible" workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p> Is <m>A</m> invertible?</p>
        <me>
          A = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp -2\\
            3 \amp 1 \amp -2\\
            -5 \amp -1 \amp 9
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            We can use IMT to determine if <m>A</m> is invertible by showing that <m>A</m> either makes at least one statement in the list true or makes at least one statement in the list false. Note that <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ -5 \amp -1 \amp 9 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</me>. We see that <m>A </m> has a pivot in every column. Therefore, by IMT, <m>A </m> must make every statment on the list true. In particular, we learn that <m>A </m> is invertible.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
 

    <example xml:id="ex-matrix-completion-singular">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each matrix below, determine all values of <m>h</m> so that the matrix is singular (not invertible).
          If there are no values of <m>h </m>, explain why.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace=".3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp  h \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp h \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp h \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Thus, <m>A </m>is missing a pivot if and only if <m>h = 0</m>. Therefore, <m>h = 0</m> is the only value of <m>h </m> which makes <m>A </m> singular.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace=".3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>B = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp h \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that regardless of the value of <m>h </m>, <m>B </m> will have a pivot in each column. Therefore, no value of <m>h </m> will make <m>B </m> singular.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace=".3in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>C = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp h \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp h \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp h-1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</me>. Thus, <m>C </m> is missing a pivot in the third row if and only if <m>h = 1</m>. Therefore, <m>h = 1</m> is the only value of <m>h</m> which makes <m>C </m> singular.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>
